The functional groups present on the surface of synthesised EBD-CD were investigated by FTIR spectroscopy (Fig. 4
                           ). The spectra of EBD-CD reveals a broad band between 3230 cm−1 to 3394 cm−1, the major peak cantered on 3394 cm−1 is assigned to OH vibrational stretching frequencies. While, the minor peak cantered on 3232 cm−1 is for NH vibration [41]. The vibrational peaks at 1705 cm−1, 1648 cm-1and 1397 cm-1are consigned to CO,CN and CN groups [42,43].The stretching vibration of CBr bond is assigned at 640 cm−1 
                           [44]. Moreover, the stretching frequencies at 1074 cm−1 and 605 cm−1 reveals the CS and CS groups [45].

The rate of corrosion of MS electrode in 15% HCl solution in the presence of inhibitor EBD-CD and EBD have been analysed by the EIS study. The Nyquist plots of uninhibited and inhibited experimental solution containing different concentrations of inhibitors have been presented in Fig. 12 . All the spectra demonstrate the single capacitive loop, this display a single time constant and involvement of the Faradic process in the charge transfer phenomenon between the experimental solution and working electrode in the corrosion process. The diameter of EIS spectra was observed to increase with the concentration of inhibitor, this suggests increase in charge transfer resistance at the metal-solution interface. The incensement in the charge transfer resistance with inhibitor concentration is due to the fabrication of protective layer of inhibitor molecules upon the MS electrode. The nature of capacitive loop is observed depressed, it indicates microscopic heterogeneity due to adsorption of inhibitor at the surface of working electrode [67,68]. All the impedance spectra were fitted against standard Randle's equivalent circuit as shown in Fig. 13 . The equivalent circuit has a charge transfer resistance (
R
ct
) that combined with a constant phase element (CPEdl) deceits in parallel to each other, whereas the solution resistance (
R s
) kept in series to them. The solution-metal interface does not behave like an ideal capacitor, to resolve the issue and for better fitting CPE is introduced in place of pure double layer capacitance.
